==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Pied
<hw>Pied</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Pie</er> the
party-colored bird.]</ety> <def>Variegated with spots of different
colors; party-colored; spotted; piebald.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Pied</xex>
coats.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Burton.</au> ⟦ldquo⟧Meadows trim with daisies
<xex>pied</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Milton.</au>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pied antelope</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the
bontebok.</cd> -- <col><b>Pied-billed grebe</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>the dabchick.</cd> -- <col><b>Pied
blackbird</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any Asiatic thrush of the
genus <gen>Turdulus</gen>.</cd> -- <col><b>Pied finch</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>The chaffinch.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd>
<cd>The snow bunting</cd>. <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> -- <col><b>Pied
flycatcher</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a common European
flycatcher (<spn>Ficedula atricapilla</spn>). The male is black and
white.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Piedmont</ent>⟦br⟧
